linux. eject usb after umount

Gemini said
In Linux, running umount unmounts the filesystem, but it doesn't necessarily "power down" the device. If your USB drive still has its lights on or you want to ensure the hardware is fully "detached" before physical removal, you usually want to follow up with an eject command.

Here is how you handle it properly from the terminal.

1. The Standard Way (Command Line)
After you have unmounted the partition, you can tell the system to logically eject the device.

Unmount the drive:
sudo umount /dev/sdb1

Eject the hardware:
sudo eject /dev/sdb

Note: Notice that in step 1, you unmount the partition (e.g., sdb1), but in step 2, you eject the entire disk (e.g., sdb).

2. The "Power Off" Way (udisksctl)
If you are on a modern distribution (Ubuntu, Fedora, etc.), udisksctl is often the preferred method because it handles both unmounting and powering off the USB port in one go, without needing sudo.

To unmount:
udisksctl unmount -b /dev/sdb1

To power off the device:
udisksctl power-off -b /dev/sdb

This is the cleanest method because it physically cuts power to the drive (the "Safe to Remove" signal).

3. Summary of Commands
Command	Action	Best For...
umount	Detaches the filesystem.	Preparing for a script or remount.
eject	Unmounts (if needed) and toggles the tray/logic.	General CLI use.
udisksctl power-off	Unmounts and cuts power to the USB.	Safest physical removal.
How to verify it's gone
Run lsblk before and after. If the device /dev/sdb no longer appears in the list, you are 100% clear to pull it out.

