You said
oh. should i umount the device, or the directory it's mounted to?

Gemini said
Technically, you can do either. Linux is flexible enough to understand what you mean, but there are subtle differences in how the system handles the request.

1. Unmounting the Directory (The "Path" Method)
If you know where the drive is attached (e.g., /media/usb-drive), this is often the most intuitive way.

Command: sudo umount /media/usb-drive

Best for: When you are already working in the terminal near that folder.

2. Unmounting the Device (The "Source" Method)
This targets the hardware partition directly (e.g., /dev/sdb1).

Command: sudo umount /dev/sdb1

Best for: When the mount point has a long or complex name, or if you aren't sure exactly where it was mounted.

Which is "Better"?
While both work, unmounting by the directory is slightly safer in a multi-user environment. If you accidentally have the same device mounted in two different places (rare, but possible), unmounting the directory ensures you are only closing the specific "access point" you intended.

However, the device method is usually faster if you just ran lsblk to see what's plugged in.

The "Target Busy" Error
Regardless of which one you choose, you might see this:
umount: /media/usb-drive: target is busy.

This happens if:

You are physically in the folder: Your terminal's "current working directory" is inside the USB. (Solution: cd ~)

A file is open: You have a photo, document, or code file open from that drive.

A process is using it: A file manager or background task is indexing the drive.

The Pro Tip: eject handles it all
If you use the eject command mentioned earlier, you don't even have to worry about umount first. Running eject /dev/sdb will automatically attempt to unmount all partitions on that device before disconnecting it.

